We recommended that management require the Municipal Treasurer to:

Demand submission of Accountable Forms/Official Receipts still in the hands of three Collectors and account the collections and deposit immediately to the authorized government depository bank;
Impose the daily turn-over of collections by the Revenue Officers/ collectors. See to it that close monitoring on the frequency of turn-over of the collections be strictly imposed.
Deposit intact all collections with the authorized depository bank daily, or not later than the next banking day, to ensure protection from possible misuse of government funds; 
Ensure that there is proper physical count of the accountable forms remaining in the custody of the collectorsand check the same to the new balances on  hand column in the DSCAF;
Keep adequate permanent record book and that will contain all the information as set forth in Section 95 of the GAAM, Volume 1;
Strictly follow the use of RIS for an accurate utilization/issuance of accountable forms and establish responsibility on the AF issued to collectors;
Require the Revenue Collectors to prepare the RAAF and then prepare CRAAF to consolidate the RAAFs.  Submit the required monthly reports in the prescribed forms provided in the NGAS Manual and submit the same not later than the fifth day of the ensuing month to the audit team;
Strictly observe daily recording of collections and deposits in the cashbooks;
Reconcile the cashbooks against the cash on hand on a daily basis for accuracy of balance at any given time;

We recommended that management require the Municipal Treasurer to:

Impose the daily turn-over of collections by the Revenue Officers/ collectors to the Municipal Treasurer;
Strictly observe daily recording of collections and deposits in the cashbooks;
Reconcile the cashbooks against the cash on hand on a daily basis for accuracy of balance at any given time; and
Deposit intact all collections with the authorized depository bank daily, or not later than the next banking day, to ensure protection from possible misuse of government funds.

We recommended that management require the Municipal Treasurer to:
Demand submission of Accountable Forms/Official Receipts still in the hands of three Collectors and account the collections and deposit immediately to the authorized government depository bank;
Impose the daily turn-over of collections by the Revenue Officers/ collectors. See to it that close monitoring on the frequency of turn-over of the collections be strictly imposed.
Deposit intact all collections with the authorized depository bank daily, or not later than the next banking day, to ensure protection from possible misuse of government funds;
Ensure that there is proper physical count of the accountable forms remaining in the custody of the collectors and check the same to the new balances on  hand column in the DSCAF;
Keep adequate permanent record book and that will contain all the information as set forth in Section 95 of the GAAM, Volume 1;
Strictly follow the use of RIS for an accurate utilization/issuance of accountable forms and establish responsibility on the AF issued to collectors;
Require the Revenue Collectors to prepare the RAAF and then prepare CRAAF to consolidate the RAAFs.  Submit the required monthly reports in the prescribed forms provided in the NGAS Manual and submit the same not later than the fifth day of the ensuing month to the audit team;
Strictly observe daily recording of collections and deposits in the cashbooks;
Reconcile the cashbooks against the cash on hand on a daily basis for accuracy of balance at any given time;
Submit justifications for still giving responsibility as collecting agents despite of failure to turn-over collections in due time.

Further, we recommended to the management to demand the immediate restitution and deposits of the government funds on the hand of the Municipal Treasurer and collectors and cause the proper accounting of assets and income accounts in the books of the Municipality.

We recommended that BAC Secretariat:
Submit copy of infrastructure contracts to COA within five working days from perfection thereof for review and evaluation pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-001;
Document and monitor the flow or movement of the contracts to establish accountability for the non-submission of contracts for audit.

In view of the foregoing we recommended that:

The Local Finance Committee make a systematic and realistic forecasting of revenue taking into account prior years’ experience and statistics as aids in setting targets.  Review of the present budgeting done under the stewardship of the Municipal Budget Office should be undertaken to set a clearer guide per item of revenue account for the Municipal Treasurer’s Office towards attaining the targets set;

The Municipal Treasurer make a periodic review whether collection targets are attained.  Conduct periodic review of accomplishments in order to have assurance that all revenue sources are tapped to maximize the revenue generating powers mandated by law. The reasons for the shortfalls in collections should be analyzed and alternative actions should be looked into to avoid incurrence of shortfall in the future;

The Municipal Accountant make a proper adjusting entries in the books of accounts the collections on “ante and post mortem inspection fee” for a total amount of P412,178.00 which were erroneously recorded in the Trust Fund; and

The Treasury and Accounting Departments accomplish Quarterly Report of Income (LBAc Form No. 1) on periodic basis so as to keep track of the status of revenue generation and at the same time adopt measures that will likely improve collections for accounts not reaching the targets.  This will provide the assurance that more plans and programs will be fully implemented.
